00:03:36.187 --> 00:03:43.249
Asteroids are objects that orbit the sun, much like planets, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, and so on.

00:03:44.118 --> 00:03:47.828
They are essentially remnants of the early solar system,

00:03:48.268 --> 00:03:51.718
chunks of rock and metal that never formed into planets.

00:03:52.872 --> 00:03:58.442
The difference between an asteroid and a planet mainly comes down to size.

00:03:59.353 --> 00:04:03.543
Planets are much bigger, therefore have a larger gravitational

00:04:03.543 --> 00:04:07.133
pull, and are circular in shape, because of gravity.

00:04:08.853 --> 00:04:14.773
Asteroids are smaller, typically ranging from a few hundred metres or so through

00:04:14.773 --> 00:04:18.953
to the largest known asteroid, which is almost 1,000 kilometres in diameter,

00:04:19.383 --> 00:04:24.533
around the same width as France from its most northern to most southern point.

00:04:25.203 --> 00:04:28.323
It’s pretty big, but it’s much smaller than a planet.

00:04:29.056 --> 00:04:32.856
And because they are much smaller, they have a much lower gravitational

00:04:32.856 --> 00:04:36.476
pull, so they’re not typically round but more like a rock.

00:04:38.066 --> 00:04:43.206
Most known asteroids are in the asteroid belt, which is between Mars

00:04:43.206 --> 00:04:47.906
and Jupiter, but not all; there are others that come closer to Earth.

00:04:48.306 --> 00:04:51.276
Some come too close, like the one that is thought to have

00:04:51.276 --> 00:04:55.066
hit Earth and wiped out the dinosaurs 66 million years ago.

00:04:55.786 --> 00:05:00.616
Fortunately, we humans are better than dinosaurs at spotting potential threats in the sky,

00:05:00.866 --> 00:05:05.656
so in the event of an asteroid looking like it was on a collision path with Earth, we would

00:05:05.656 --> 00:05:11.276
know about it pretty quickly and be more capable than a diplodocus of changing its trajectory.

00:05:11.996 --> 00:05:16.526
So, we know where asteroids are, and because they orbit the sun,

00:05:16.906 --> 00:05:20.766
it is fairly easy to model their position at any point in time.

00:05:22.216 --> 00:05:27.046
And while 19th-century astronomers might not have known much about the

00:05:27.066 --> 00:05:32.641
consistency of an asteroid, or what it is actually made out of, we now do.

00:05:33.521 --> 00:05:39.211
Some asteroids are thought to contain incredibly high levels of precious metals.

00:05:40.411 --> 00:05:45.501
When the solar system was formed, heavy elements like gold, platinum,

00:05:45.731 --> 00:05:49.151
nickel, and iron were distributed throughout the massive cloud

00:05:49.151 --> 00:05:52.741
of gas and dust that eventually became the Sun and the planets.

00:05:54.001 --> 00:05:59.771
These elements were created during supernova explosions and collisions of neutron

00:05:59.771 --> 00:06:05.111
stars—cosmic events that forge the universe’s heaviest and most valuable materials.

00:06:06.431 --> 00:06:11.681
When the solar system began to take shape, gravity caused much of the

00:06:11.681 --> 00:06:16.861
heavy material to sink towards the cores of the newly forming planets.

00:06:17.681 --> 00:06:22.431
On Earth, for example, most of the gold and platinum we know of is thought

00:06:22.431 --> 00:06:26.851
to be buried deep within the planet’s core, out of reach for humans.

00:06:28.233 --> 00:06:32.423
But not all of this material ended up inside planets.

00:06:33.016 --> 00:06:37.536
Some of it remained as loose chunks of rock and metal scattered

00:06:37.576 --> 00:06:40.336
throughout the solar system—what we now call asteroids.

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:46.630
These asteroids are essentially the leftover building blocks of planets, and many

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:51.260
contain high concentrations of metals that didn’t make it into planetary cores.

00:06:52.170 --> 00:06:57.020
But what makes these asteroids so appealing isn’t just their high metal

00:06:57.030 --> 00:07:02.240
content—it’s that the metals are often much more accessible than on Earth.

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:07.920
Unlike Earth, where heavy metals have sunk to the core, asteroids

00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:10.880
haven’t undergone the same processes of differentiation.

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:15.040
This means that their metals are distributed throughout their

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:19.490
structure, making them, in theory at least, easier to extract.

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:26.086
As I’m sure you will know, mining almost anything on Earth, and especially mining

00:07:26.086 --> 00:07:32.059
precious metals, is a dirty, intensive and expensive activity, often carried

00:07:32.059 --> 00:07:36.949
out by people, sometimes even children, working in pretty awful conditions.

