Cobalt, for example, is a vital part of electric batteries, and

00:07:42.342 --> 00:07:46.852
70% of all cobalt is produced in the Democratic Republic of Congo.

00:07:47.772 --> 00:07:53.941
And conditions in the Congolese cobalt mines have been likened to modern-day slavery.

00:07:55.041 --> 00:07:58.091
Cobalt and Congo are just one example.

00:07:58.641 --> 00:08:04.581
Getting anything out of the Earth’s crust is an intensive, polluting process, so

00:08:05.071 --> 00:08:09.631
wouldn’t it be better, the argument goes, for us just to take it from an asteroid?

00:08:10.074 --> 00:08:13.381
There would be no pollution, no child labour, and

00:08:13.381 --> 00:08:16.591
no destruction of forests to make way for the mines.

00:08:17.443 --> 00:08:20.200
In theory, it all sounds very positive.

00:08:20.510 --> 00:08:25.330
A lifetime’s supply of precious metals floating around in the sky, fortunes

00:08:25.330 --> 00:08:29.420
to be made for anyone who can find a way to go up there and get them.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:33.100
Of course, it's more complicated than that.

00:08:33.818 --> 00:08:38.270
First, let’s talk about the practicality of getting to an asteroid.

00:08:38.970 --> 00:08:40.420
They are a long way away.

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:46.690
In late 2023 NASA did actually send a mission to the asteroid

00:08:46.690 --> 00:08:49.166
Psyche, the one I mentioned at the start of the episode.

