Its scheduled arrival date is 2029, so it will take 6 years for it to get there.

00:08:57.746 --> 00:09:03.686
It’s travelling at something like 50,000 kilometres an hour, incredibly fast by Earth

00:09:03.696 --> 00:09:09.856
standards, the problem is that it needs to travel almost 500 million kilometres to get there.

00:09:11.256 --> 00:09:16.606
And it isn’t on a space mining mission, but rather a fact-gathering one.

00:09:17.246 --> 00:09:23.346
No spacecraft has ever been to Psyche before, so the plan is to go and observe it.

00:09:24.816 --> 00:09:29.961
Given the cost of getting to an asteroid, any mission needs to be fairly sure that it

00:09:29.961 --> 00:09:36.056
will find what it’s looking for, and given that not all asteroids are created equal–some

00:09:36.056 --> 00:09:40.846
are rocky, others are icy, and others contain high levels of precious metals–you

00:09:40.846 --> 00:09:45.846
need to send a fact-finding mission first before committing to a mining mission.

00:09:46.736 --> 00:09:49.046
Now, let’s talk about costs.

00:09:49.611 --> 00:09:53.367
A large proportion of the cost of any space mission is getting

00:09:53.407 --> 00:09:56.567
out of the Earth’s atmosphere, and then returning safely.

00:09:57.777 --> 00:10:04.459
Sending something to space is expensive, but it is considerably cheaper than it used to be.

00:10:05.679 --> 00:10:11.999
During the first thirty years or so of space launches, it would typically cost in the region of

00:10:12.069 --> 00:10:21.153
$25,000 per kilo to send something to space, but some projects were upwards of $100,000 per kilo.

00:10:22.623 --> 00:10:27.693
Companies such as SpaceX have been hyper-focused on reducing the

00:10:27.723 --> 00:10:33.914
cost of going to space so that it now costs around $1,500 per kilo.

00:10:35.145 --> 00:10:40.873
But with reusable rockets and increasing efficiencies in every part of the launch

00:10:40.883 --> 00:10:45.873
process, there are some estimates that this could be brought down to around

00:10:46.153 --> 00:10:53.003
$10 per kilo, less than it would cost to send a 1 kilo parcel within the UK.

00:10:53.873 --> 00:10:58.933
So, yes going to space and therefore getting to an asteroid is very

00:10:58.933 --> 00:11:04.403
expensive, but while a few decades ago it would have been so expensive that

00:11:04.403 --> 00:11:08.973
it simply wouldn’t have been economically viable, now it very well might be.

00:11:09.923 --> 00:11:14.213
So, let’s assume that costs have gone down to such an extent

00:11:14.443 --> 00:11:18.203
that the first asteroid mining mission is ready for lift-off.

00:11:18.673 --> 00:11:19.643
How would it work?

00:11:20.423 --> 00:11:25.583
Well, there are several fundamental differences between Earth and Space that mean

00:11:25.583 --> 00:11:30.173
an asteroid mine certainly wouldn’t bear much resemblance to any mine on Earth.

00:11:30.969 --> 00:11:35.312
Obviously, there is the problem of how to get all of the equipment there, so it

00:11:35.322 --> 00:11:39.462
simply wouldn’t be possible to boost large trucks and heavy equipment into space,

00:11:39.962 --> 00:11:44.914
and anyhow, this kind of equipment would probably be of little use on an asteroid.

00:11:45.537 --> 00:11:51.137
There is no gravity on an asteroid, so everything would need to be tied down to the asteroid.

00:11:51.868 --> 00:11:56.462
Most probably, there would be some kind of great canopy, a tent-like

00:11:56.462 --> 00:12:00.722
structure, that was put over the area that was being mined, otherwise,

00:12:00.802 --> 00:12:04.972
all of the dust and precious metals would simply blow away into space.

00:12:06.412 --> 00:12:12.622
And in terms of the mining process, there are several different ideas about how this could work.

00:12:13.257 --> 00:12:18.337
Perhaps it would be lasers that would vaporise material, robotic arms that

00:12:18.337 --> 00:12:23.197
grind and collect it, or even specialised bacteria, as they do in terrestrial

00:12:23.207 --> 00:12:28.757
biomining, that break down rock and release valuable metals like nickel or cobalt.

00:12:29.707 --> 00:12:32.977
Another significant challenge is that asteroids typically

00:12:32.977 --> 00:12:36.817
rotate, often unpredictably and at varying speeds.

00:12:37.287 --> 00:12:40.917
This constant movement makes it very difficult to safely land

00:12:40.917 --> 00:12:44.707
equipment, maintain stability, or accurately mine materials.

00:12:45.457 --> 00:12:48.637
To address this, the mining team would need to find some

00:12:48.637 --> 00:12:52.487
way of stabilising the asteroid, keeping it in position.

00:12:53.187 --> 00:12:57.717
Maybe this would be using thrusters to slow or stop its rotation.

00:12:57.947 --> 00:13:02.647
Maybe it would be by using large nets or tethers to anchor it, or

00:13:02.647 --> 00:13:06.607
by synchronising mining tools to match the asteroid’s rotation.

00:13:07.547 --> 00:13:11.687
And then there is the question of who would work on the mine.

00:13:12.697 --> 00:13:17.277
This is not a question of whether there would be thousands of astronauts with hammers

00:13:17.277 --> 00:13:22.067
and shovels physically digging the surface themselves, and lugging large sacks back at

00:13:22.067 --> 00:13:28.047
the end of the day, but rather whether the mine would be 100% automated, controlled from

00:13:28.047 --> 00:13:33.447
back on Earth or from a space mission closer to Earth, or whether there would be human

00:13:33.514 --> 00:13:38.438
astronauts  monitoring the situation from the site, just in case anything went wrong.

00:13:39.311 --> 00:13:41.823
And there is also the legal question.

00:13:42.745 --> 00:13:46.515
One of the very first episodes we ever made, more than 5

00:13:46.515 --> 00:13:50.655
years ago now, was about the question of who owns space.

00:13:51.595 --> 00:13:55.865
5 years on, that question still remains largely unanswered.

00:13:57.015 --> 00:14:03.025
The first principle of the 1967 Space Treaty is, and I’m quoting directly, “the

00:14:03.055 --> 00:14:08.255
exploration and use of outer space shall be carried out for the benefit and

00:14:08.315 --> 00:14:13.795
in the interests of all countries and shall be the province of all mankind”

00:14:15.226 --> 00:14:20.840
And it is shortly followed by “outer space is not subject to national appropriation

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:25.870
by claim of sovereignty, by means of use or occupation, or by any other means”.

00:14:27.123 --> 00:14:29.923
In other words, nobody owns space.

00:14:30.633 --> 00:14:35.743
But there is a grey area over what this means in terms of asteroid mining.

00:14:36.543 --> 00:14:42.683
If a company successfully mines an asteroid, who owns the minerals they mine?

00:14:43.763 --> 00:14:47.483
Is it a bit like fishing, where any boat can fish in international

00:14:47.483 --> 00:14:51.373
waters, and they are free to use and sell what they catch?

00:14:52.153 --> 00:14:53.413
Or is it not?

00:14:54.512 --> 00:15:00.652
In 2015, Barack Obama signed something called the SPACE Act, which gives U.S.

00:15:00.652 --> 00:15:05.252
citizens the right to "engage in the commercial exploration and

00:15:05.252 --> 00:15:09.622
exploitation of 'space resources' [including ... water and minerals]

00:15:10.932 --> 00:15:16.122
".
In other words, US citizens can do it, according to US law at least.

00:15:16.472 --> 00:15:20.002
But how does this law play with international law?

00:15:21.362 --> 00:15:28.192
It hasn’t been an issue so far, because nobody has done it, but if asteroid mining turns

00:15:28.252 --> 00:15:34.212
from the theoretical to the practical, it is a question that will need to be addressed.

00:15:35.088 --> 00:15:41.558
Now, let’s assume that it is addressed, and that companies are able to build cost-effective

00:15:41.568 --> 00:15:46.248
ways of getting mining equipment to space, and successfully mining an asteroid.

00:15:47.398 --> 00:15:48.468
What happens next?

00:15:49.288 --> 00:15:53.558
Well, there is also the question of where the minerals go.

00:15:54.938 --> 00:15:59.398
One option is to bring them back to Earth and use them here.

00:16:00.216 --> 00:16:06.107
We need the minerals found on asteroids, especially the platinum group metals, we need them here on

00:16:06.107 --> 00:16:12.705
Earth, for everything from batteries to solar panels to electric cars, so there is a clear demand.

00:16:13.348 --> 00:16:18.326
Whoever can bring them back cost effectively will become spectacularly wealthy.

00:16:19.226 --> 00:16:24.716
But the other option is to leave them in space, for use in space.

00:16:25.778 --> 00:16:30.308
The more activity there is in space, the more stuff is needed, and this currently

00:16:30.358 --> 00:16:35.338
all needs to be brought from Earth and then sent to space, which is expensive.

00:16:36.468 --> 00:16:39.228
No matter how plentiful and cheap something might be

00:16:39.228 --> 00:16:42.978
on Earth, in space it suddenly becomes very expensive.

00:16:44.158 --> 00:16:46.758
One obvious example is water.

00:16:47.828 --> 00:16:53.448
A kilo of water might be practically free on Earth, but taking a kilo of

00:16:53.448 --> 00:16:58.428
water to space costs the same as taking a kilo of anything else to space.

00:16:59.486 --> 00:17:04.452
And in space, water is incredibly important and in short supply.

00:17:05.743 --> 00:17:10.713
Water is needed to keep astronauts hydrated, as well as for cooling and

00:17:10.713 --> 00:17:14.832
regulating the temperature of a spacecraft, and as a radiation shield.

00:17:15.632 --> 00:17:23.403
But perhaps even more important than this are the component parts of water; hydrogen and oxygen.

00:17:24.323 --> 00:17:30.323
The oxygen can be separated from the water, and can be used for breathing on a spacecraft.

00:17:31.073 --> 00:17:36.943
Liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen are the primary propellants of many modern rockets,

00:17:37.293 --> 00:17:43.853
so if water can be found on an asteroid, for example, it becomes incredibly valuable.

00:17:44.633 --> 00:17:50.635
There are no petrol stations in space, all fuel needs to be brought up from Earth,

00:17:51.071 --> 00:17:58.333
but if a source of water, in the form of ice or water-rich material, could be found,

00:17:58.722 --> 00:18:04.123
and this could be processed in space into rocket fuel and left in space, where it

00:18:04.123 --> 00:18:09.033
is most useful and valuable, then this would be like a petrol station in space.

00:18:09.523 --> 00:18:14.152
It would bring down the cost of space launches, because they wouldn’t have to take so

00:18:14.153 --> 00:18:20.723
much fuel up from Earth, and it would allow for longer and faster journeys within space.

00:18:22.253 --> 00:18:27.731
And perhaps veering even more into the realms of the ultra-futuristic, in a

00:18:27.731 --> 00:18:32.535
universe in which there were settlements on other planets, Mars, for example, it

00:18:32.535 --> 00:18:38.705
makes much more sense to manufacture what is needed in space rather than on Earth.

00:18:39.313 --> 00:18:43.758
If you need to build a settlement, it could be a lot more cost effective to take the

00:18:43.778 --> 00:18:48.948
raw materials from a nearby asteroid than shooting them up from a rocket on Earth.

00:18:50.028 --> 00:18:53.668
So, one option is to leave the mined materials in space.

00:18:54.307 --> 00:18:59.498
But what would happen if these rare minerals were brought back down to Earth?

